"Bauwens M., Ohlsson H., Barbé K., Beelaerts V., Dehairs F., Schoukens J.","On climate reconstruction using bivalves: Three methods to interpret the chemical signature of a shell",2011,"Computer Methods and Programs in Biomedicine","104","2",,"104","111",,,10.1016/j.cmpb.2010.08.020,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80054096214&partnerID=40&md5=75a1068e1c9ae7542f69f9650aaf1b8e","Department of Fundamental Electricity and Instrumentation, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium; Department of Earth System Sciences and Analytical and Environmental Chemistry, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium; Division of Automatic Control, Department of Electrical Engineering, Linköping University, SE-581 83 Linköping, Sweden","Bauwens, M., Department of Fundamental Electricity and Instrumentation, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium, Department of Earth System Sciences and Analytical and Environmental Chemistry, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium; Ohlsson, H., Division of Automatic Control, Department of Electrical Engineering, Linköping University, SE-581 83 Linköping, Sweden; Barbé, K., Department of Fundamental Electricity and Instrumentation, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium; Beelaerts, V., Department of Fundamental Electricity and Instrumentation, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium; Dehairs, F., Department of Earth System Sciences and Analytical and Environmental Chemistry, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium; Schoukens, J., Department of Fundamental Electricity and Instrumentation, Vrije Universiteit Brussel, Pleinlaan 2, 1050 Brussel, Belgium","To improve our understanding of the climate process and to assess the human impact on current global warming, past climate reconstruction is essential. The chemical composition of a bivalve shell is strongly coupled to environmental variations and therefore ancient shells are potential climate archives. The nonlinear nature of the relation between environmental condition (e.g. the seawater temperature) and proxy composition makes it hard to predict the former from the latter, however. In this paper we compare the ability of three nonlinear system identification methods to reconstruct the ambient temperature from the chemical composition of a shell. The comparison shows that nonlinear multi-proxy approaches are potentially useful tools for climate reconstructions and that manifold based methods result in smoother and more precise temperature reconstruction. © 2010 Elsevier Ireland Ltd.","Bivalve; Climate reconstruction; Manifold learning; Nonlinear multi-proxy models; Sclerochronology; Support Vector Regression","Bivalve; Climate reconstruction; Manifold learning; Nonlinear multi-proxy models; Sclerochronology; Support Vector Regression; Global warming; Seawater; Shells (structures); accuracy; animal anatomy; article; bivalve; chemical composition; data analysis; environmental temperature; machine learning; nonhuman; prediction; shell; statistical analysis; support vector machine; Animals; Bivalvia; Climate; Seawater",,,,,,"Verheyden, A., De Ridder, F., Schmitz, N., Beeckman, H., Koedam, N., High-resolution time series of vessel density in Kenyan mangrove trees reveal a link with climate (2005) New Phytologist, 167 (2), pp. 425-435; Davis, B.A.S., Brewer, S., Stevenson, A.C., Guiot, J., The temperature of Europe during the Holocene reconstructed from pollen data (2003) Quaternary Science Reviews, 22 (15-17), pp. 1701-1716. , Data Contributors; Klein, R.T., Lohmann, K.C., Thayer, C.W., Bivalve skeletons record sea-surface temperature and δ18O via Mg/Ca and 18O/16O ratios (1996) Geology, 24, pp. 415-418; Vander Putten, E., Dehairs, F., Keppens, E., Baeyens, W., High resolution distribution of trace elements in the calcite shell layer of modern Mytilus edulis: environmental and biological control